Project Introduction¶

Goal:¶

Discover the profile of high-value customers for a client's 3 product line segments: sweettreats, flavorfirst and modernhealth.

Method:¶

Create a scikit-learn model to predict 3 segments' spendings over customers' other available information using a Tweedie regression model.

Data:¶

Individual level data of demographic and purchase info aggregated over one year period:

  • demographic information of the purchaser,
  • total spending, units, and counts (number of months when any purchase was made) of any item (not limited to the 3 segments) over a year.
  • spending, units and counts (number of months when any purchase was made) within the 3 segments over a year.

1.2 Define modeling variables¶

  • define explantory variables (predictor), target variables (response), and variables for normalization, etc.
  • target variables are spending features of the 3 segments: sweettreats, flavorfirst and modernhealth.
  • normalization variable consider high spending is correlated with high units and counts.
  • exposure variable is a feature in tweedie model that defines a span of time interval.
In [9]:
#Define explantory variable, target variable, variable for normalization, etc
target_var_list = ['sweettreats_spend','sweettreats_units', 'sweettreats_count',
                   'flavorfirst_spend','flavorfirst_units', 'flavorfirst_count',
                   'modernhealth_spend','modernhealth_units', 'modernhealth_count',
                   ]
normalize_var_list = ['total_units','total_spend','total_count']
exclude_list = ['countintab',]
# exposure_var for tweedie model
exposure_var = 'total_count'
df_X = df[df.columns[~df.columns.isin(target_var_list+exclude_list+normalize_var_list)]]

  • among total spending features, segment spending also mostly correlates with total units.
  • making total units a potential normalizing variable.

model_dict = {}
for i in target_var_list:
    
    #Use mask to select only positive values, because Tweedie only works in positive values
    mask=df_train[i]>0
    print(i)
    model = TweedieRegressor(power=1.9, alpha=1, max_iter=10000)
    
    #The response variable is normalized by the exposure variable
    model.fit(X_train[mask], df_train[i][mask],sample_weight=df_train[exposure_var][mask])
    model_dict[i] = model

def score_estimator(
    estimator, X_train, X_test, df_train, df_test, target, weights,
    tweedie_powers=None,
):
    """Evaluate an estimator on train and test sets with different metrics"""

    metrics = [
        ("D² explained", None),   # Use default scorer if it exists
        ("mean abs. error", mean_absolute_error),
        ("mean squared error", mean_squared_error),
    ]
    if tweedie_powers:
        metrics += [(
            "mean Tweedie dev p={:.4f}".format(power),
            partial(mean_tweedie_deviance, power=power)
        ) for power in tweedie_powers]

    res = []
    for subset_label, X, df in [
        ("train", X_train, df_train),
        ("test", X_test, df_test),
    ]:
        y, _weights = df[target], df[weights]
        for score_label, metric in metrics:
            if isinstance(estimator, tuple) and len(estimator) == 2:
                # Score the model consisting of the product of frequency and
                # severity models.
                est_freq, est_sev = estimator
                y_pred = est_freq.predict(X) * est_sev.predict(X)
            else:
                y_pred = estimator.predict(X)

            if metric is None:
                if not hasattr(estimator, "score"):
                    continue
                score = estimator.score(X, y, sample_weight=_weights)
            else:
                score = metric(y, y_pred, sample_weight=_weights)

            res.append(
                {"subset": subset_label, "metric": score_label, "score": score}
            )

    res = (
        pd.DataFrame(res)
        .set_index(["metric", "subset"])
        .score.unstack(-1)
        .round(4)
        .loc[:, ['train', 'test']]
    )
    return res

#Define function to plot 
def plot_obs_pred(df, X, feature, target, model, exposure, y_label=None,
                  ax=None, fill_legend=False):
    """Plot observed and predicted - aggregated per feature level.

    Parameters
    ----------
    df : DataFrame
        input data
    feature: str
        a column name of df for the feature to be plotted
    weight : str
        column name of df with the values of weights or exposure
    observed : str
        a column name of df with the observed target
    predicted : DataFrame
        a dataframe, with the same index as df, with the predicted target
    fill_legend : bool, default=False
        whether to show fill_between legend
    """
    
    title = 'test '+ feature
    
    # aggregate observed and predicted variables by feature level
    df_ = df.loc[:, [feature]].copy()
    df_["observed"] = df[target] 
    df_["predicted"] = model.predict(X) *df[exposure]
    df_ = (
        df_.groupby([feature])[["observed", "predicted"]]
        .sum()
        .assign(observed=lambda x: x["observed"])
        .assign(predicted=lambda x: x["predicted"])
    )

    ax = df_.loc[:, ["observed", "predicted"]].plot(style=".", ax=ax)
    y_max = df_.loc[:, ["observed", "predicted"]].values.max() * 0.8
    p2 = ax.fill_between(
        df_.index,
        0,
        y_max,
        color="g",
        alpha=0.1,
    )
    if fill_legend:
        ax.legend([p2], ["{} distribution".format(feature)])
    ax.set(
        ylabel=y_label if y_label is not None else None,
        title=title if title is not None else "Train: Observed vs Predicted",
    )

from sklearn.utils import gen_even_slices
def _mean_frequency_by_risk_group(y_true, y_pred, sample_weight=None,
                                  n_bins=100):
    """Compare predictions and observations for bins ordered by y_pred.

    We order the samples by ``y_pred`` and split it in bins.
    In each bin the observed mean is compared with the predicted mean.

    Parameters
    ----------
    y_true: array-like of shape (n_samples,)
        Ground truth (correct) target values.
    y_pred: array-like of shape (n_samples,)
        Estimated target values.
    sample_weight : array-like of shape (n_samples,)
        Sample weights.
    n_bins: int
        Number of bins to use.

    Returns
    -------
    bin_centers: ndarray of shape (n_bins,)
        bin centers
    y_true_bin: ndarray of shape (n_bins,)
        average y_pred for each bin
    y_pred_bin: ndarray of shape (n_bins,)
        average y_pred for each bin
    """
    idx_sort = np.argsort(y_pred)
    bin_centers = np.arange(0, 1, 1/n_bins) + 0.5/n_bins
    y_pred_bin = np.zeros(n_bins)
    y_true_bin = np.zeros(n_bins)

    for n, sl in enumerate(gen_even_slices(len(y_true), n_bins)):
        weights = sample_weight
        y_pred_bin[n] = np.average(
            y_pred[idx_sort][sl], weights=weights
        )
        y_true_bin[n] = np.average(
            y_true[idx_sort][sl],
            weights=weights
        )
    return bin_centers, y_true_bin, y_pred_bin

def _mean_frequency_by_risk_group(y_true, y_pred, sample_weight=None,
                                  n_bins=100):
    """Compare predictions and observations for bins ordered by y_pred.

    We order the samples by ``y_pred`` and split it in bins.
    In each bin the observed mean is compared with the predicted mean.

    Parameters
    ----------
    y_true: array-like of shape (n_samples,)
        Ground truth (correct) target values.
    y_pred: array-like of shape (n_samples,)
        Estimated target values.
    sample_weight : array-like of shape (n_samples,)
        Sample weights.
    n_bins: int
        Number of bins to use.

    Returns
    -------
    bin_centers: ndarray of shape (n_bins,)
        bin centers
    y_true_bin: ndarray of shape (n_bins,)
        average y_pred for each bin
    y_pred_bin: ndarray of shape (n_bins,)
        average y_pred for each bin
    """
    idx_sort = np.argsort(y_pred)
    bin_centers = np.arange(0, 1, 1/n_bins) + 0.5/n_bins
    y_pred_bin = np.zeros(n_bins)
    y_true_bin = np.zeros(n_bins)

    for n, sl in enumerate(gen_even_slices(len(y_true), n_bins)):
        weights = sample_weight
        y_pred_bin[n] = np.average(
            y_pred[idx_sort][sl], weights=weights
        )
        y_true_bin[n] = np.average(
            y_true[idx_sort][sl],
            weights=weights
        )
    return bin_centers, y_true_bin, y_pred_bin

4.2 Use Lorenz curve to determine the model power in predicting the testing values¶

  • random baseline: no prediction power
  • oracle (grey): perfect prediction power
  • oracle (green): predicting power using only exposure variable
In [72]:
def lorenz_curve(y_true, y_pred):
    y_true, y_pred = np.asarray(y_true), np.asarray(y_pred)

    # order samples by increasing predicted risk:
    ranking = np.argsort(y_pred)
    ranked_pure_premium = y_true[ranking]
    cumulated_claim_amount = np.cumsum(ranked_pure_premium)
    cumulated_claim_amount = cumulated_claim_amount/cumulated_claim_amount[-1]
    cumulated_samples = np.linspace(0, 1, len(cumulated_claim_amount))
    return cumulated_samples, cumulated_claim_amount

for var, model in model_dict.items():
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 8))

    # Get final prediction by multiplying model prediction with normalizing factor (exposure variable)
    y_pred_total = model.predict(X_test)*df_test[exposure_var].values
    
    #Curve for the model
    for label, y_pred in [(var, y_pred_total)]:        
        ordered_samples, cum_claims = lorenz_curve(df_test[var], y_pred)
        gini = 1 - 2 * auc(ordered_samples, cum_claims)
        label += " (Gini index: {:.3f})".format(gini)
        ax.plot(ordered_samples, cum_claims, linestyle="-", label=label)

    # Oracle model1 (grey): y_pred == y_test
    ordered_samples, cum_claims = lorenz_curve(df_test[var], df_test[var])
    gini = 1 - 2 * auc(ordered_samples, cum_claims)
    label = "Oracle (Gini index: {:.3f})".format(gini)
    ax.plot(ordered_samples, cum_claims, linestyle="-.", color="gray",
            label=label)
    
    # Oracle model2 (green): Predict using exposure_var
    ordered_samples, cum_claims = lorenz_curve(df_test[var], df_test[exposure_var])
    gini = 1 - 2 * auc(ordered_samples, cum_claims)
    label = "Oracle (Gini index: {:.3f})".format(gini)
    ax.plot(ordered_samples, cum_claims, linestyle="-.", color="green",
            label=label)

    # Random baseline
    ax.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], linestyle="--", color="black",
            label="Random baseline")
    ax.set(

        ylabel='Fraction of total target'
    )

Step5. Conclusion and suggestion¶

Conclusion¶

  • The model distinguishes high-value customers for a client's 3 product line segments: sweettreats, flavorfirst and modernhealth.
  • Surprisingly the most predicting power came from the normalization variable: total units.
  • I suspect total units serves as a proxy to the number of purchasing trips.
  • While there is no reason to believe there is information leak from total spending features to segment spending, household demographic was ruled out from being a significant factor.
  • There is likely latent features which is unseen in this project that determines this unexpected result.

Suggestion¶

  • Ideally I want to collect trip-wise data (the spending features of each trip), as month-wise data deosn't yield enough resolution.
  • Once with the trip-wise data, it is possible to model the number of trips in a poisson regression.
  • Alternatively with the trip-wise data, it is possible to model the segment spending in a tweedie regression.
  • Future model can also log transform the spending or unit of segment spending as their histogram shows signs of exponential decay.
  • It should not matter whether data aggregation to month or year was used, because poisson or tweedie regression should work for any time interval.
